	<h1>Input</h1>

	The previous examples have been about <strong>output</strong>, usually in response to a <strong>page render request</strong>.<br/>
	Your page can handle these requests by providing <em>setupRender()</em>, <em>cleanupRender()</em>, <em>onPassivate()</em>, etc.<br/><br/> 
	
	Now we look at <strong>input</strong>. In Tapestry, input is sent to the server in a <strong>component event request</strong>.<br/>
	As we will see, your page can handle events with methods like <em>onValidate()</em>, <em>onSuccess()</em>, etc.<br/><br/>
	
	There are 3 main components that send component event requests: EventLink, ActionLink, and Form.<br/>

	<ul>
		<li><strong>EventLink</strong> passes input in the URL of the request (an HTTP GET).</li>
		<li><strong>ActionLink</strong> also passes input in the URL of the request (an HTTP GET). It is very similar to EventLink.</li>
		<li><strong>Form</strong> passes input in the body of the request (an HTTP POST).</li>
	</ul>
	 
	There are also components that send AJAX component event requests which we will look at later.<br/><br/> 
	
	When a component event request reaches the server, Tapestry activates the page and notifies the corresponding component in the page.<br/>
	The component then "bubbles up" one or more events to its containing component, which is typically the page.

	<ul>
		<li>EventLink "bubbles up" an event with whatever name you chose, eg. ViewPerson.</li>
		<li>ActionLink "bubbles up" the event ACTION.</li>
		<li>Form "bubbles up" several events including VALIDATE, SUCCESS, and FAILURE.</li>
	</ul>  

	If the containing component (eg. the page) has appropriate event handler methods (eg. <em>onValidate()</em>) then Tapestry will call them.<br/><br/>

	The examples that follow demonstrate EventLink, ActionLink, and Form.<br/><br/>

	References:	
	<a href="http://tapestry.apache.org/page-navigation.html">Page Navigation</a>, 
	<a href="http://tapestry.apache.org/component-events.html">Component Events</a>.<br/><br/>
	
